                {"src": "ellicott", "attr": "Ellicott's Commentary", "html": "<p>Impossible! Rather let God be seen to be true though all mankind should be proved false, even as the Psalmist looked upon his own sin as serving to enhance the triumph of God's justice. Speaking of that justice for the moment as if arraigned before a higher tribunal, he asserts its absolute and complete acquittal.</p>"},
                {"src": "barnes", "attr": "Barnes' Notes", "html": "<p>The veracity of God was a great fundamental principle; to admit any question of it would shake the foundations of all religion. God should be esteemed true to all his promises, threatening, and declarations; and rather than admit that any word of his had failed, we should regard every man as false and erring.</p>"},
                {"src": "rwp", "attr": "Robertson's Word Pictures", "html": "<p>\"Let God continue to be true\" (present middle imperative). The contrast means, \"though every man be found a liar.\" Psalm 51:6 — \"That thou mightest be justified\" — Paul uses the LXX closely, where David's confession of sin becomes the occasion for God's righteousness to be publicly displayed.</p>"}
