                {"src": "barnes", "attr": "Barnes' Notes", "html": "<p>The Jews supposed that God was the God of their nation only, that they alone were to be admitted to his favour. Paul showed that as all had alike sinned — Jews and Gentiles — and as the plan of salvation by faith was adapted to sinners without special reference to Jews, so God could show favour to all, and all might be admitted on the same terms.</p>"},
                {"src": "rwp", "attr": "Robertson's Word Pictures", "html": "<p>Of Gentiles also (<em>καὶ ἐθνῶν</em>). Jews overlooked it then and some Christians do now. The parenthesis Paul inserts — \"yes, of Gentiles also\" — is brief because it needs no argument; it follows necessarily from the oneness of God.</p>"}
