                {"src": "ellicott", "attr": "Ellicott's Commentary", "html": "<p>The argument is strictly logical. If there is to be any distinction between Jew and Gentile, this can only be upon the assumption either that there are more gods than one, or that they will be justified by some different law in some different way. But neither is the case. Therefore it follows that there is no distinction.</p>"},
                {"src": "clarke", "attr": "Adam Clarke's Commentary", "html": "<p>It is one and the same God who made both Jews and Gentiles, who shall justify the circumcision — the believing Jews — by faith; and the uncircumcision — the believing Gentiles — by the same faith; as there is but one Savior and one atonement provided for the whole. It is fanciful to suppose any real difference in the two prepositions Paul uses.</p>"},
                {"src": "rwp", "attr": "Robertson's Word Pictures", "html": "<p><em>By faith</em> (<em>ἐκ πίστεως</em>) — \"out of faith,\" denoting source. <em>Through faith</em> (<em>διὰ τῆς πίστεως</em>) — \"by means of the faith\" just mentioned. <em>Ἐκ</em> denotes source, <em>διά</em> intermediate agency or attendant circumstance — both make faith the operative ground.</p>"}
