                {"src": "clarke", "attr": "Adam Clarke's Commentary", "html": "<p>By law here we may understand three things: (1) the whole of the Mosaic law — accomplished in Christ's passion; (2) the moral law — faith does not abrogate it but empowers its fulfilment; (3) the law and prophets — all of whose testimony the gospel vindicates and confirms. Faith establishes all three.</p>"},
                {"src": "ellicott", "attr": "Ellicott's Commentary", "html": "<p>It seems right to take this as an isolated statement to be worked out afterwards (Romans 6:1 <em>et seq.</em>) more fully. The Apostle deals with two objections to justification by faith: that there ought to be a different rule for Jew and Gentile (v. 29), and that the law is thereby abolished. He meets the second by flat contradiction — it is not abolished, but confirmed.</p>"},
                {"src": "rwp", "attr": "Robertson's Word Pictures", "html": "<p>Paul hinted at this in verse 21 and will show in chapter 4 how Abraham illustrates the very point. Besides, apart from Christ and the help of the Holy Spirit no one can keep God's law. The Mosaic law is only workable by faith in Christ — so faith, far from voiding it, is the prerequisite for its genuine fulfilment.</p>"}
